Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 42nd Weekly Dose of Optimism.
It was honestly hard to choose what to include and what to cut this week be=
cause so much good/big/optimistic news dropped over the past few days.=20
Energy. AI. Cancer Vaccines. The important stuff that makes our lives bette=
r and helps our civilization progress.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Axios [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/3690793f-a2a7-4694-9104-001294ab71b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Axios Pro [ https://substack.com/redirect/3690793f-a2a7-4694-9104-001294ab7=
1b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is=
 your personal deals analyst, helping you navigate the fast-paced world of =
VC, PE and M&A. Each day, Axios=E2=80=99 industry-leading journalists deliv=
er exclusive reporting sourced from insider connections that other=C2=A0new=
s outlets just don't have. All that, plus a daily deals list, in just 5 min=
utes.
Not Boring subscribers can=C2=A0take 50% off Axios Pro=C2=A0by using code=
=C2=A0NOTBORING=C2=A0at checkout. Start your free trial now [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/3690793f-a2a7-4694-9104-001294ab71b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
(1) Microsoft Bets That Fusion Power Is Closer Than Many Think [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/6d010bf2-4d46-4656-9094-e9033183d432?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Jennifer Hiller [ https://substack.com/redirect/27a88a95-9ddc-4c3c-8862-64d=
681a80b5d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] for The Wall Street Journal
In a deal that is believed to be the first commercial agreement for fusion =
power, the tech giant has agreed to purchase electricity from startup Helio=
n Energy within about five years. Helion, which is backed by OpenAI founder=
 Sam Altman, committed to start producing electricity through fusion by 202=
8 and target power generation for Microsoft of at least 50 megawatts after =
a year or pay financial penalties.
Sam Altman. So hot right now. Sam Altman.
As if leading the generative AI renaissance wasn=E2=80=99t enough, Altman=
=E2=80=99s nuclear fusion company, Helion, just inked the first ever commer=
cial nuclear fusion deal. The deal between Helion and Microsoft is a bold o=
ne: it=E2=80=99s based on Helion=E2=80=99s commitment to start producing an=
d providing electricity through fusion in the next 5 years. The main hurdle=
 is, of course, that neither Helion nor any other organization in the world=
 has  ever produced commercial-scale electricity through fusion.
Fusion is the Holy Grail of energy. As Altman put it, the promise of fusion=
 is that it will =E2=80=9Cpower the world and to do it extremely cheaply.=
=E2=80=9D Such abundant, cheap energy would have second and third order eff=
ects on progress that are hard to predict. However, nuclear fusion has been=
 one of those technologies that=E2=80=99s always, as Fran Fraschilla* would=
 say, =E2=80=9Ca couple years away from being a couple years away.=E2=80=9D
When scientists at the National Ignition Facility at Lawrence Livermore Nat=
ional Laboratory finally achieved net energy gain [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/bb3c1df5-cc45-4b7f-9f27-8d790dd57227?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in December 2022, the excitement was =
matched with reminders that commercialization of fusion might still be deca=
des away. Welp, at least on paper, the commercialization of fusion is upon =
us.
Whether Helion hits the 2028 goal or not =E2=80=94 and it has to pay financ=
ial penalties to Microsoft if it doesn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=94 absurdly ambitio=
us timelines can be useful in accelerating entire industries. See: Tesla an=
d SpaceX. =20
*Yes, we just quoted basketball scout Fran Fraschilla in our analysis of nu=
clear fusion.=20
(2) US support for nuclear power soars to highest level in a decade [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/c3f7db3f-7d2a-4012-b3b2-b9b289f1faf1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Akielly Hu [ https://substack.com/redirect/fb0ecce6-1273-41de-924a-5f612167=
f8f4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or Grist
A Gallup survey [ https://substack.com/redirect/0154a7b3-3deb-4e3d-b38a-b2b=
650d11b27?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] released in late April found that 55 percent of U.S. adults support the=
 use of nuclear power. That=E2=80=99s up four percentage points from last y=
ear and reflects the highest level of public support for nuclear energy use=
 in electricity since 2012.=C2=A0
Not be outdone by its nuclear brother, nuclear fission is also having a bit=
 of a moment. The oft-misunderstood energy source, which produces about ~20=
% of electricity in the U.S., reached its highest level of support in the U=
S since 2012.
As we wait for truly commercially available nuclear fusion, increased nucle=
ar fission energy output presents one of the best paths towards a cleaner e=
nergy future. Despite its current output and future potential, nuclear fiss=
ion struggles from a pretty bad stigma that prevents it from gaining widesp=
read support. The public stigma stems from two primary sources:
Historical Events: Chernobyl in 1986, the Three Mile Island in 1979, and Fu=
kushima in 2011.=20
Lack of Understanding/Word Association: People associate nuclear power with=
 nuclear bombs. Not a great comp! Second, people are afraid of nuclear wast=
e and radiation. Third, it=E2=80=99s hard to not worry when you think Homer=
 Simpson is responsible for keeping you safe. D=E2=80=99oh!=20
But when you peel back the stigma, it becomes quite obvious that the promis=
e of nuclear far outweighs the negative. Or at least, that=E2=80=99s an opi=
nion, according to this Gallup survey that more and more Americans are star=
ting to adopt.=20
That=E2=80=99s a good backdrop for nuclear startups. A couple weeks ago, a1=
6z=E2=80=99s American Dynamism practice announced [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/832fcb30-50a1-40b0-95ee-f7a75dd11869?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that it=E2=80=99s leading the Series =
B for Radiant Industries [ https://substack.com/redirect/2ed2f68c-8e3f-4c20=
-99f8-100762f04ebd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], which =E2=80=9Cis building portable 1-megawatt nuclear reacto=
rs, the size of a shipping container, that can reliably produce power for 2=
0 years.=E2=80=9D We=E2=80=99re pretty excited about Aalo Atomics [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/b69bd9de-89c6-4eed-a2f2-4b01d2376412?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], too.=20
(3) Google I/O 2023 Keynote [ https://substack.com/redirect/176d6eb4-7880-4=
708-9800-df36198fe65a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
(Relevant Generative AI Search section starts at here [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/0245ff58-53ce-444f-8d62-0e8eb465df08?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ])
OpenAI is old news.=20
Google Search is the future of AI.
But 99% of you idiots don=E2=80=99t even know how to use it.
Here are 69 ways to boost your productivity using Google AI =F0=9F=91=87
So, Google came out swinging this week with the full reveal of how it is in=
fusing AI across its suite of products. Admittedly, we haven=E2=80=99t done=
 a deep-dive on how the keynote was received (other than just watching smas=
hups of Sundar saying AI repeatedly) but at first glance: this was a strong=
 response from Google.
In =E2=80=9CThe Unbearable Heaviness of Being Positioned [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/8cc60c76-f873-49e4-898=
d-311a0feede97?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=E2=80=9D Packy argued that Go=
ogle was so deeply Positioned in search, which it monetizes through links, =
that it was susceptible to a potentially superior search product that deliv=
ered answers, like ChatGPT.
It=E2=80=99s obviously too early to tell, but based on the demo this week, =
it seems like Google may have found a nice middle ground. Build AI-powered =
search that provides answers and build monetizable links/modules into those=
 answers.
Ultimately, competition is good for consumers and, in generative AI, we=E2=
=80=99re getting that in spades right now. Google vs. OpenAI vs. Meta vs. a=
ny number of smaller, fast-moving startups. It=E2=80=99s going to push inno=
vation, force companies to really build for users, and ultimately result in=
 better products.
(4) Sohn 2023 | Patrick Collison in conversation Sam Altman [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/6357cc65-f884-4ec6-9c3b-3556afebe025?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The Sohn Conference was held virtually this last Tuesday, and it was filled=
 with heavy hitters and cross over interviews that nerds us like dream abou=
t (all of which you can find here [ https://substack.com/redirect/11310c4b-=
646e-4e3c-a770-fece79a6c10f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]). O=E2=80=99Shaughnessy x Karniol-Tambour. Sokoloff x=
 Druckenmiller. And of course, Collison x Altman.
It=E2=80=99s not super often that you get to watch the CEO of one tech darl=
ing (Stripe) interview the CEO of another (OpenAI). Aside from Altman=E2=80=
=99s insights on the current and future landscape of AI and some great disc=
ussion across a number of progress-related topics, it=E2=80=99s kind of coo=
l to watch Collison jab Altman with jokes about SBF and Worldcoin. Maybe th=
ese guys aren=E2=80=99t that different from us, after all.=20
And like most of us, Altman mostly uses ChatGPT for summarizing stuff and h=
asn=E2=80=99t fully adopted the other uses cases or plugins.
So the next time you see some dumb thread about all of the 10x productivity=
 hacks you=E2=80=99re missing out on by not using AI properly, just remembe=
r Sam Altman basically just uses it to read emails more quickly.=20
(5) Pancreatic Cancer Vaccine Shows Promise in Small Trial [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/4ac0d73e-c7d3-4e2a-9c3f-063000479b71?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Benjamin Mueller [ https://substack.com/redirect/38c91365-2c21-4b44-923c-e2=
60ec4646c2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for The New York Times
On Wednesday, the scientists reported results [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/e07b24d3-baa2-467c-96c7-2d4b7527b24f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that defied the long odds. The vaccine pr=
ovoked an immune response in half of the patients treated, and those people=
 showed no relapse of their cancer during the course of the study, a findin=
g that outside experts described as extremely promising.
Abstracting away much of the scientific complexity, here=E2=80=99s what hap=
pened: a team of researchers at BioNtech developed personalized vaccines th=
at successfully provoked an autoimmune response in pancreatic cancer patien=
ts and those people showed no relapse of their cancer during the course of =
the study.
While the study was small and the commercialization of the vaccines is stil=
l early, this was a milestone for personalized cancer vaccines. The team wa=
s able to develop and deliver personalized and efficacious vaccines to pati=
ents within roughly 9 weeks of having their tumors removed. It=E2=80=99s no=
t hard to imagine a world in which there is almost instantaneous developmen=
t and delivery of highly personalized vaccines that treat all kinds of dise=
ases.
Here=E2=80=99s to a world in which nuclear fusion is providing abundantly c=
heap energy to power endless AI search and instantaneously personalized and=
 delivered vaccines.
Bonuses: Humans did more amazing stuff this week than we could fit, so if y=
ou want a little extra, check out how generative AI is building better anti=
bodies [ https://substack.com/redirect/042cd3ff-f0f0-487c-8bff-621b20ec9418=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], smel=
ling things in the metaverse [ https://substack.com/redirect/ac6b7a54-b963-=
426d-82e6-c4ceb66c45c7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and some space porn via James Webb [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/41953dac-2112-4ef3-b6d1-4ffd87d34e9a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Mo=
nday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan

